Let $f(x)$ be a real-valued function defined on the interval $[-\pi, \pi]$ with the property that $f(x) = f(-x)$ for all $x$ in the interval, and let $g(x) = x^2 - \pi^2$. The loyal Northwestern Wildcat fan, who is also a mathematician, wants to find a real number $c$ in the interval $[-\pi, \pi]$ such that
\begin{equation*}
\int_{-\pi}^{\pi} f(x)g(x) \, dx = c \int_{-\pi}^{\pi} f(x) \, dx.
\end{equation*}
What is $c$?
